Over the weekend I watched the making of south park doc on a whim and it was fascinating watching these guys trap themselves in perpetual crunch and their work reflecting that.

I don't watch south park at all but I always assumed that their super fast turnaround was designed to immediately respond to the present culture, but no, it's the other way around. All they can do is respond to the present because their workflow and brand doesn't let them go beyond that.

They only have 6 days to work an episode so the only material they're able to come up with is what's trending + some crude twist that came up between guys shooting the shit. Emphasis on "guys shooting the shit" - I can deal with crudeness, its the cheap, exclusionary injoke vibe that makes me wince.

I admire the grind! They push out work without letting perfectionism crush them! Their great voice acting makes the show! But to see these guys in their late thirties (at time of doc) make early newgrounds level humor for this long when actual newgrounds animators grew out of it by their age is AUGH

People tend to get the idea of what an 'infinite' is versus what a 'loop' is.

Infinites:
-Keep going til an opponent dies, runs out of time, or even after that.
-work if there's no infinite prevention system in place.

Loops:
-Repeatable combo sequence that only lasts as long as the game allows.

For loops, what I mean is usually games have hit decay or juggle limits that could prevent you from doing certain things in a combo. I wouldn't call it an infinite prevention system because it usually would just be hard cutoff like what JJBAHFTF has. You can do whatever you want til it stops you.

So I finally got on with watching #Gundam: Requiem For Vengeance. Still got 2 episodes to go but it‚Äôs‚Ä¶fine. I wish I could be more glowing but it‚Äôs‚Ä¶fine. I like how it effectively portrays how terrifying the Gundam could be to fight, kinda like how they do it in the Cucuruz Doan manga.

I also think it‚Äôs cool in the second episode to watch the characters piloting a Zaku tank with the cockpit partially exposed because it‚Äôs been cut open on one side. It‚Äôs something I don‚Äôt recall seeing too much in Gundam. That was neat.

I don‚Äôt dislike the characters. Solari is a perfectly fine lead, though I hope we get to see more of her backstory before the end. Also, and I admit this is a small point, but I don‚Äôt like how the characters don‚Äôt look like they don‚Äôt belong in the year 0079.
It‚Äôs something that always kinda irks me when you have a new tale set during a particular part in the timeline of a franchise, but the characters look like they‚Äôre from a different era.

I actually felt this way about GQuuuuuuX too. Like, I know it‚Äôs not the same world exactly, but should the characters in 0085 be kinda dressed like characters in Zeta Gundam since that took place in the original timeline‚Äôs 0087?
And that‚Äôs not to say the character designs look bad in either of these, it‚Äôs just a small thing that bothers me when I see it happen in anything.

Anyway, Requiem For Vengeance. It‚Äôs okay. Definitely not the best short series Gundam has to offer. Like, it‚Äôs nowhere near as good as 0080 or even 0083. If anything it reminds me of MS-Igloo which I was also kinda lukewarm towards. Have to see how I feel by the end of the show, I guess.

I'm going to cover the Pokrovsk front a little more thoroughly today and explain what's going on right now.
After all, we have stopped the Russians and taken back the following communities and areas around them: Kotlyne, Pishchane, Uspenivka and Lysivka.

All these communities were of the utmost strategic importance to even launch the attack on Pokrovsk. Now our troops are concentrating on taking Shevchenko, because when we take that small town, the Ryzzen front southwest of Pokrovsk collapses.

The Ryzzen try to get maintenance to Shevchenko, but our drone units observe them and destroy them regularly. The Russians would be short of food, water and ammunition right now, yet they attack relentlessly. Of course, all their attacks are repulsed and the thinning of the orcs is ruthless.

Shevchenko is also the last Ryzka stronghold on higher ground on the southwestern flank. When we take the city, we have complete fire control in the area and the ryzka must get out of the immediate area. Everyone remembers the stinging criticism

of the 155th Brigade, but it is precisely it, together with the 45th, that is now beating the Russians. The brigade has gained more experience and has been reinforced with veterans to maximize the mix of old and new.

The strategy has paid off and the brigade is approaching elite level. It is constantly equipped with French weapons and equipment.
Right now I am in communication with the units that we intend to visit on Pokrovskfront

to make a risk assessment of the situation, I am not alone on the journey. The important thing is to know that we are not going to interfere if they are going to make an attack. In the past, the units have been on defense, but slowly and surely

the situation is changing to an offensive. The garage is full of products to be delivered, especially candlesticks are in demand.
The other good news is that we have liberated a 2 km x 2 km area at Nadiia, Kharkiv Region. The tourists have moved their units

from here to Kursk and therefore we were able to liberate a lot of forest and windbreak with a small squad. When our military leadership realizes that the enemy has removed enough troops, we strike. Fabio has

taken care of other fronts.
Finally, I would like to clarify some facts that remove the cloak of Trumpet's and the media's headline. Ukraine is not Ryzzland where a dictator decides everything,
but we are a democracy with a constitution that governs and decides how things should be handled. This means that it is currently not legal to hold presidential

or parliamentary elections, it should be the Western media emphasizes more than putting the headline ‚ÄúUkraine agrees to new elections‚Äù.
